Unknown Businesses Of Punjab. Day 04 Of 28 Days, 28 States & Their Unknown Businesses. . . . . . Welcome to the vibrant state of Punjab, where tradition meets innovation. Join us on a journey through the diverse industries that make Punjab a powerhouse of economic growth and cultural richness. Punjab is the breadbasket of India, producing a whopping 16% of the nation's wheat and 10% of its rice. With 60% of its population working in agriculture, it's no wonder major FMCG giants like Pepsico, Coca-cola, ITC, Nestle, and Cargill have a significant presence here. If bicycles are your passion, Punjab is the place to be. It's home to 92% of India's bicycle parts production and 75% of the country's bicycles. Companies like Hero, Atlas, and Avon Cycles roll out top-quality bikes, with 80% of India's bicycle exports proudly bearing the Punjab mark. Punjab is the heartbeat of India's machinery and hand tool manufacturing industry, producing drill machines, electric saws, hammers, and more. Ludhiana and Jalandhar are the epicenters of this industry, contributing 20% of India's output. Punjab is a textile powerhouse, producing 65% of hosiery and a whopping 95% of woolen clothes in all of India. Its cotton yield per hectare is the highest in the nation, and with three huge textile parks, it caters to global fashion giants like GAP, Zara, and Puma. Punjab is a champion in the sports goods industry, accounting for 75% of India's production. From cricket gear to equipment for global events like the Tokyo Olympics and Commonwealth Games, Punjab's sports goods find their way onto the world stage. Follow @physicsloverz for more Margaret Heafield Hamilton was an American computer scientist, systems engineer, and business owner. She was Director of the Software Engineering Division of the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory, which developed on-board flight software for the Apollo space program. In 1986, she became the founder and CEO of Hamilton Technologies, Inc., in Cambridge, Massachusetts. The company was developed around the Universal Systems Language based on her paradigm of Development Before the Fact (DBTF) for systems and software design. Hamilton has published over 130 papers, proceedings, and reports about the 60 projects and six major programs in which she has been involved. On November 22, 2016, she was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by U.S. President Barack Obama for her work leading the development of on-board flight software for NASAâ€™s Apollo Moon missions.
